# Act One

= A radio operator picks up a signal that shouldn't exist.

FADE IN:

INT. RADIO OUTPOST - NIGHT

Snow batters the small window. LIV (30s, sleep-deprived) adjusts dials on an old radio set.

Static. Then, faintly:

VOICE (V.O.)
(through the radio, distorted)
...anyone receiving...repeat...

LIV
(sitting up straight)
Hello? Hello, come in.

Nothing but static.

LIV (CONT'D)
(to herself)
That frequency's been dead for thirty years.

She scribbles notes: *time, frequency, duration.*

CUT TO:

EXT. OUTPOST - CONTINUOUS

The antenna sways in the wind, ice clinging to every strut.

INT. RADIO OUTPOST - LATER

Liv hasn't slept. Coffee mugs pile up beside her.

LIV
(into the radio)
If you can hear me, say something. Anything.

VOICE (V.O.)
(clearer now)
...Liv? Is that you?

Liv freezes, hand hovering over the dial.

LIV
(barely audible)
That's not possible.

= End of Act One. Liv realizes the voice knows her name.

# Act Two

INT. OUTPOST - STORAGE ROOM - DAY

Liv digs through old crates, pulling out a decades-old logbook.

[[Note: logbook prop needs to look handwritten, 1990s era]]

She flips to the final entry, dated the night the station went dark.

LIV
(reading)
"If you're hearing this, don't answer back."

>SHE SITS WITH THAT FOR A LONG MOMENT.<

TECH VOICE (O.S.)
(over intercom)
Liv, we're losing the uplink. Wrap it up.

LIV
(shouting back)
Two minutes!

She turns back to the radio, hand trembling.

FADE OUT.

> THE END OF ACT TWO <
